Below are the variable descriptions, taken directly from the midterm assignment instructions.

There are 7 categorical variables:

  • game_name: name of the video (nominal variable)
  • game_publisher: publishing company for the game (nominal)
  • game_metascore: ranking of the quality of the game (ordinal)
  • game_free: whether the game free or not (TRUE or FALSE; nominal, binary)
  • release_day: day in the month the game was released (ordinal)
  • release_month: month in the year the game was released (ordinal)
  • release_year: year the game was released (ordinal)

There are 2 continuous variables:

  • game_price: price of the game in US dollars
  • median_playtime: median playtime for the game in minutes (this seems to be rounded to the nearest integer)

3 Categorical variables

In this section, I explore counts of the categorical variables. I will ignore game_name because that is more like an identifier as well as game_free because theres only one category represented here (none of the games were free!).

3.1 game_metascore

This variable is missing a lot of observations. Later, it might be interesting to look at which game_publishers have the highest and lowest ranking games, but it would be hard to gauge whether this is meaningful with the large number of missing meta scores there are.

Meta scores range from 23 to 93.

Below, I plot a bar chart of the counts of meta scores, but there are too many categories, so I condense some of these rankings into bins. Also, I remove the missing observations so that their count doesnt appear in the bar chart.

df %>%
  select(game_metascore) %>%
  na.omit() %>%
  mutate(metascore_group = ifelse(game_metascore < 30, "20-29", 
                                  ifelse(game_metascore >= 30 & game_metascore < 40, "30-39",
                                         ifelse(game_metascore >= 40 & game_metascore < 50, "40-49",
                                                ifelse(game_metascore >= 50 & game_metascore < 60, "50-59",
                                                       ifelse(game_metascore >= 60 & game_metascore < 70, "60-69",
                                                              ifelse(game_metascore >= 70 & game_metascore < 80, "70-79", "80-93"))))))) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = metascore_group)) +
  geom_bar() +
  geom_text(stat = 'count',
            mapping = aes(label = stat(count)),
            size = 5, color = 'blue', nudge_y = 7) +
  theme_bw()

Assuming that these meta scores are on a 0 to 100 scale it seems that most of these games are generally of good to great quality (i.e., with meta scores above 60).

df %>%

There is a peak around 50 games (per game publisher) and it looks like there are a few publishers with more than 100 games. I think 75 and 100 are a good cut-offs for lumping the publishers together.

df %>% 
  mutate(game_publisher = forcats::fct_lump_min(game_publisher, 75)) %>% 
  mutate(game_publisher = forcats::fct_infreq(game_publisher)) %>%

  geom_bar() +
  geom_text(stat = 'count',

            size = 5, color = 'blue', nudge_x = 75) +
  theme_bw()

df %>% 
  mutate(game_publisher = forcats::fct_lump_min(game_publisher, 100)) %>% 
  mutate(game_publisher = forcats::fct_rev(game_publisher)) %>% 
  filter(game_publisher != "Other") %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = game_publisher)) +
  geom_bar() +

3.3 release_day and weekday

I dont think its that interesting to see what day of the month the games were released. However, I do think that the day of the week would be interesting to look at so I explore that below.

df %>% 
  #make weekday variable
  mutate(date = paste0(release_year, "-", release_month, "-", release_day),
         date = as.Date(date),
         weekday = wday(date,
                        label = TRUE)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = weekday)) +
  geom_bar() +
  geom_text(stat = 'count',
            mapping = aes(label = stat(count)),
            size = 5, color = 'blue', nudge_y = 20) +
  theme_bw()

It looks like most games are released on Thursdays, Fridays, and Tuesdays. My housemate just mentioned that releasing video games on Tuesday is an industry standard (but I dont know when this started), so I wonder if Tuesday-released games are more frequent in more recent years, so even though there are bit more Thursday and Friday releases in this data set, these numbers may be driven by older release days. Ill explore this later.

Below, I plot a bar chart showing the number of games released per weekday by year. I examine the proportions instead of raw counts, sort of as a way to account for the fact that more games were released in later years overall.

df %>% 
  mutate(date = paste0(release_year, "-", release_month, "-", release_day),
         date = as.Date(date),
         weekday = wday(date, label = TRUE),
         month = month(date, label = TRUE),
         year = year(date)) %>%
  mutate(year_group = cut(year, breaks = 6)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = year)) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(fill = as.factor(weekday)),
           position = 'fill') +
  ggthemes::scale_fill_colorblind('weekday') +
  labs(y = 'conditional proportion of game releases') +
  theme_bw()

It does not seem like more games get released on Tuesdays more often as the years pass. The proportion of games released on Tuesdays is relatively constant, especially from 2010 to 2018. However, the proportion of games released on Thursdays has grown since 2012 and the proportion of games released on Fridays has fluctuated a lot, relative to other weekdays.

4.2 release_month x release_year

In this section, I examine which months have the most games released across the years.

df %>% 
  mutate(date = paste0(release_year, "-", release_month, "-", release_day),
         date = as.Date(date),
         weekday = wday(date, label = TRUE),
         month = month(date, label = TRUE),
         year = year(date)) %>%
  count(release_month, release_year) %>%
  arrange(desc(n)) %>%
  head(n = 15)

If I look at all years and all months, and consider the raw counts of releases, it looks like the most games were released in 2018 or 2017 in the winter (Jan, Feb, Mar) or fall/winter months (Sept, Oct, Nov). However, more games were released overall in more recent years, so it would be helpful to look at proportions or split the plots up by year (e.g., facets might be easier to look at than grouped plots) and allow the y-axis scale to vary.

df %>% 
  mutate(date = paste0(release_year, "-", release_month, "-", release_day),
         date = as.Date(date),
         weekday = wday(date, label = TRUE),
         month = as.factor(month(date)),
         year = year(date)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = month)) +
  geom_bar() +
  facet_wrap(~year,
             ncol = 3,
             scales = "free_y") +
  labs(y = 'conditional proportion of game releases') +
  theme_bw()

Across the years below, the top few months (based on visual inspection of the plots above) with the greatest number of game releases are:

  • 2004 - February, June, November
  • 2005 - May, October
  • 2006 - July, October, December
  • 2007 - March, August
  • 2008 - April, October
  • 2009 - February, November
  • 2010 - June, October, November
  • 2011 - January, September, November
  • 2012 - May, October, November
  • 2013 - August to December
  • 2014 - April, May
  • 2015 - September, November
  • 2016 - June, July, September
  • 2017 - August to December
  • 2018 - January to March, September

Overall, if we just look at the number of releases by month or year, we observe that more games were released in September and from 2016 to 2017, respectively. However, looking at these conditional counts, we see that the months with the greatest number of releases varies by year. For instance, game releases occurred more frequently in September in more recent years.

Also, there seem to be more apparent peaks in video game releases in earlier years. In other words, it is easier to see these peaks or identify which months had more game releases in earlier years. For instance, in 2004 and 2007, when relatively less games were being made, publishers were obviously releasing most of their games during particular months (3 distinct months in 2004 and 2 in 2007). As more games were getting made, they were generally getting released throughout the year. We still see two peaks in almost every plot from 2012 and on, so it seems like publishers tend to release more games during certain months, but those peaks are less sharp. Im not sure if sharp is the right word, but I guess Im trying to say that the release of games during particular months becomes less prominent as time goes on (Im so bad with words I dont know if prominent is right either, but I think you get what I mean!).

  theme_bw()

Big name video game publishers werent making a lot of lowly priced games. With the exception of SEGA, the other top publishers did NOT make any games that were less than 1 dollar. On the flip side, publishers in the Other group, which comprises of companies who produced less games relative to these top four, were producing games that were very cheap.

Now, its easier to see that, for games with median play times above 0 minutes, Ubisoft has games with the greatest average median play time, followed by publishers in the Other category and then SEGA.

On average, Ubisoft has the greatest game price and median play time. Im wondering if, within the top 4 publishers and Ubisofts games, and for play times above 0, there is a relation between game prices and median play times.

df %>%
  filter(game_publisher %in% c("Ubisoft", "SEGA", "Big Fish Games", "Strategy First")) %>%
  filter(median_playtime > 0) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = game_price, y = median_playtime)) +
  geom_point(alpha = .33, size = 2) +
  theme_bw()

df %>%
  filter(game_publisher == "Ubisoft") %>%
  filter(median_playtime > 0) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = game_price, y = median_playtime)) +
  geom_point(alpha = .33, size = 2) +
  theme_bw()

It doesnt look like there is a relation between game price and median play times in either of these scenarios. It is the case that some more expensive games have higher play times, but overall, all game prices are associated with really low median play times (around 0 minutes).
